<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-adding-and-subtracting-matrices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Adding and Subtracting Matrices</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Perform addition and subtraction of compatible matrices
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                   To motivate adding and subtracting matrices with a real-world example. To explain why matrices need to be the same size for us to add and subtract them.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="mango-shopping">
        <statement>
            <p> Kelvin and Esther are buying mangoes, oranges, and bananas from a store in Soy. Kelvin buys 5 mangoes, 2 oranges, and 1 banana, while Esther buys 6 mangoes, 1 orange, and 3 bananas.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We can represent Kelvin's purchases in a <term>matrix</term>: <me>
                                \mathbf{K} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
                            </me>
                            What does the second column represent?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                The second column represents the number of oranges Kelvin bought.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p> Gently guide Learners if they struggle associating the items in a matrix with the fruits.</p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Can you write a matrix <m>\mathbf{E}</m> for Esther's purchases?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                <me>
                                    \mathbf{E} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We can represent both Kelvin and Esther's purchases in one matrix <m>\mathbf{S}</m>:
                            <me>
                                \mathbf{S} = \begin{bmatrix}  5 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 6 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                            </me>
                            What does the third column (the last vertical strip) represent?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                The third column represents the number of bananas that Kelvin and Esther bought, respectively.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p> Remind Learners what columns and rows are, if needed. </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What does the second row (the last horizontal strip) represent?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                The second row represents the number of mangoes, oranges, and bananas that Esther bought.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Visiting a Second Shop</title>
                <p>
                    Let's say the shop in Soy didn't have all the fruits Kelvin and Esther wanted, so they travelled to Webuye. They told us their purchases in this matrix <m>\mathbf{W}</m>:
                    <me>
                        \mathbf{W} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
                    </me>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Describe in words what they bought in Webuye.
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Kelvin bought 5 bananas, while Esther bought 2 mangoes and 3 oranges.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                How many mangoes, oranges, and bananas did Kelvin and Esther purchase overall? Could you represent this as a matrix?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Kelvin bought 5 mangoes, 2 oranges, and 6 bananas, while Esther bought 8 mangoes, 4 oranges, and 3 bananas. We can represent this in the matrix:
                                    <me>
                                        \mathbf{S} + \mathbf{W} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 6 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \amp 6 \\ 8 \amp 4 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                                    </me>
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                            <note component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    If Learners initially write their answers not in matrix form, ask them how they might use a matrix. Ask what they did to each cell to get the total matrix. 
                                </p>
                            </note>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What does <m>\mathbf{S} - \mathbf{W}</m> represent in this context? How would you compute it?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    <m>\mathbf{S} - \mathbf{W}</m> represents the difference between Kelvin and Esther's purchases in Soy and their purchases in Webuye. In other words, how much more they bought in Soy. We can compute it by subtracting corresponding entries of the two matrices:
                                    <md>
                                        \mathbf{S} - \mathbf{W} =\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \amp 1 \\ 6 \amp 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 5 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \amp -4 \\ 4 \amp -2 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}
                                    </md>
                                    For example, the entry in the bottom left means that Esther bought 4 more mangoes in Soy than Webuye, and the entry in the top right means that Kelvin bought 4 <em>less</em> bananas in Soy than Webuye.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                            <note component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Ask Learners what negative entries in <m>\mathbf{S} - \mathbf{W}</m> mean.
                                </p>
                            </note>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Visiting a Third Shop!</title>
                <p>
                    Murunga heard that, at a third shop, Kelvin bought 2 apples and Esther bought 5. He wrote this information in the following matrix:
                    <me>
                        \mathbf{M} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}
                    </me>
                    Murunga says to find the total amount of each fruit bought from all three shops, we can just add <m>\mathbf{S} + \mathbf{W} + \mathbf{M}</m>. Is he right? Why, or why not?
                </p>
                <solution component="lesson-plan">
                    <p>
                        Murunga is not right. We cannot add <m>\mathbf{M}</m> to <m>\mathbf{S} + \mathbf{W}</m> because the entries in these matrices do not correspond, and the matrices have different dimensions. The first column of <m>\mathbf{S} + \mathbf{W}</m> represents mangoes, while the only column of <m>\mathbf{M}</m> represents apples. Adding these doesn't tell us how much of each fruit Kelvin and Esther bought.
                    </p>
                </solution>
                <note component="lesson-plan">
                    <p>
                        If learners add the column vector to the first column of <m>\mathbf{S} + \mathbf{W}</m>, ask them what these columns represent. In <m>\mathbf{M}</m> it represents apples, but in <m>\mathbf{S}</m> and <m>\mathbf{W}</m> it represents mangoes. Adding these doesn't tell us how much of each fruit Kelvin and Esther bought.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Learners might add the column vector as a 4th column. This is good, but encourage them to see how they've created the new matrix 
                        <me>
                            \mathbf{M'} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp5 \end{bmatrix}
                        </me>
                        and then computed <m>\mathbf{S'} + \mathbf{W'} + \mathbf{M'}</m> (where <m>\mathbf{S'}</m> and <m>\mathbf{W'}</m> have an extra column of zeroes).
                    </p>
                </note>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the anchor task.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Connect the exploration from the third shop to ideas that matrices must be the same size to be added or subtracted.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Build on how learners added matrices from the first two shops to present the general rule for adding and subtracting matrices.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We can only add or subtract matrices of the same size (with the same number of rows <em>and</em> columns)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To add matrices, add the corresponding entries.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To subtract matrices, subtract the corresponding entries.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            For example, addition works like so:
            <md>
                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}\color{blue}{a} \amp \color{blue}{b} \\ \color{blue}{c} \amp \color{blue}{d} \\ \color{blue}{e} \amp \color{blue}{f}\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}\color{orange}{u} \amp \color{orange}{v} \\ \color{orange}{w} \amp \color{orange}{x} \\ \color{orange}{y} \amp \color{orange}{z}\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}\color{blue}{a}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{u} \amp \color{blue}{b}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{v} \\ \color{blue}{c}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{w} \amp \color{blue}{d}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{x} \\ \color{blue}{e}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{y} \amp \color{blue}{f}\,\color{black}{+}\,\color{orange}{z} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
            </md>
            And for subtraction:
            <md>
                <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}\color{blue}{a} \amp \color{blue}{b} \\ \color{blue}{c} \amp \color{blue}{d} \\ \color{blue}{e} \amp \color{blue}{f}\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}\color{orange}{u} \amp \color{orange}{v} \\ \color{orange}{w} \amp \color{orange}{x} \\ \color{orange}{y} \amp \color{orange}{z}\end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix}\color{blue}{a}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{u} \amp \color{blue}{b}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{v} \\ \color{blue}{c}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{w} \amp \color{blue}{d}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{x} \\ \color{blue}{e}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{y} \amp \color{blue}{f}\,\color{black}{-}\,\color{orange}{z} \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example xml:id="PRECALC-iIe1GfnTav" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Adding Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the sum of <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>A=\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\text{ and }B=\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 9 \\ 0 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>Add corresponding entries. Add the entry in row 1, column 1, <m>a_{11},</m> of matrix <m>A</m> to the entry in row 1, column 1, <m>b_{11},</m> of <m>B.</m> Continue the pattern until all entries have been added.</p>
        <p>
          <me>A+B=\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 9 \\ 0 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} \\ =\begin{bmatrix} 4+5 \amp 1+9 \\ 3+0 \amp 2+7 \end{bmatrix} \\ =\begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 10 \\ 3 \amp 9 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="PRECALC-LO3f2hDN2K" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Finding the Difference of Two Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the difference of <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>A=\begin{bmatrix} −2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\text{ and }B=\begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>We subtract the corresponding entries of each matrix.</p>
        <p>
          <me>A-B=\begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \\ =\begin{bmatrix} -2-8 \amp 3-1 \\ 0-5 \amp 1-4 \end{bmatrix} \\ =\begin{bmatrix} -10 \amp 2 \\ -5 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="PRECALC-7sOLc5Uao6" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Finding the Sum and Difference of Two 3 x 3 Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>:
          <md>A=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp −10 \amp −2 \\ 14 \amp 12 \amp 10 \\ 4 \amp −2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\text{ and }B=\begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 10 \amp −2 \\ 0 \amp −12 \amp −4 \\ −5 \amp 2 \amp −2 \end{bmatrix}</md>
        </p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>Find the sum.</li>
          <li>Find the difference.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p> Adding the matrices term by term: </p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A+B \amp =\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp −10 \amp −2 \\ 14 \amp 12 \amp 10 \\ 4 \amp −2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 10 \amp −2 \\ 0 \amp −12 \amp −4 \\ −5 \amp 2 \amp −2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2+6 \amp −10+10 \amp −2−2 \\ 14+0 \amp 12−12 \amp 10−4 \\ 4−5 \amp −2+2 \amp 2−2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 0 \amp −4 \\ 14 \amp 0 \amp 6 \\ −1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p> Subtracting the matrices term by term: </p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A−B \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp −10 \amp −2 \\ 14 \amp 12 \amp 10 \\ 4 \amp −2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 10 \amp −2 \\ 0 \amp −12 \amp −4 \\ −5 \amp 2 \amp −2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2−6 \amp −10−10 \amp −2+2 \\ 14−0 \amp 12+12 \amp 10+4 \\ 4+5 \amp −2−2 \amp 2+2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} −4 \amp −20 \amp 0 \\ 14 \amp 24 \amp 14 \\ 9 \amp −4 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </li>
                </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>

    

