    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
     <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-q5g1X2Lgdo" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
            <statement>
                <p>Add matrix <m>A</m> and matrix <m>B.</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>A=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 6 \\ 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp −3 \end{bmatrix}\text{ and }B=\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp −2 \\ 1 \amp 5 \\ −4 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A+B \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 6 \\ 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp −3 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp −2 \\ 1 \amp 5 \\ −4 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2+3 \amp 6+(−2) \\ 1+1 \amp 0+5 \\ 1+(−4) \amp −3+3 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp 5 \\ −3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
     <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-TQUChsY7ZQ" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <statement>
        <p>Given matrix <m>B = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m> find <m>B + B</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>B+ B = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} +  \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp 2 \\ 6 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="matrices-defined-or-not-defined-1">
            <statement>
                <p>Given the matrices</p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> X=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix},\quad
                        Y=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 6 \\ -2 \amp 0 \\ 4 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        <mrow> W=\begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 5 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},\quad
                        Z=\begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp 1 \\ 5 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 8  \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>Compute each expression, or state that it is not defined.</p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li><m>X+W</m></li>
                    <li><m>Y+Z-W</m></li>
                    <li><m>Y-Z</m></li>
                    <li><m>X-Y</m></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p><m>X</m> and <m>W</m> are both <m>2\times 3</m>, so the sum is defined.</p>
                            <p>
                                <me>
                                    X+W=\begin{bmatrix} 2+7 \amp -1+2 \amp 4+(-1) \\ 0+(-3) \amp 3+5 \amp 5+0 \end{bmatrix}
                                    =\begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ -3 \amp 8 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><m>Y+Z</m> is defined because both are <m>3\times 2</m>. However, <m>Y+Z-W</m> is not defined because <m>W</m> is <m>2\times 3</m>, which does not match <m>3\times 2</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m> are both <m>3\times 2</m>, so the difference is defined.</p>
                            <p>
                                <me>
                                    Y-Z=\begin{bmatrix} 1-(-4) \amp 6-1 \\ -2-5 \amp 0-(-2) \\ 4-0 \amp 3-8 \end{bmatrix}
                                    =\begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 5 \\ -7 \amp 2 \\ 4 \amp -5 \end{bmatrix}
                                </me>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Not defined, because <m>X</m> is <m>2\times 3</m> and <m>Y</m> is <m>3\times 2</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <title>Adding and Subtracting Magic Squares</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The two matrices below are magic squares, as introduced in <xref ref="magic-square-intro"/>. That means, for each matrix, their rows, columns, and diagonals all add to the same number.
                    <md>
                        M = \begin{bmatrix}16 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp 13\\ 5 \amp 10 \amp 11 \amp 8 \\ 9 \amp 6 \amp 7 \amp 12 \\ 4 \amp 15 \amp 14 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}\,\quad R = \begin{bmatrix} 16 \amp 10 \amp 20 \amp 3 \\3 \amp 19 \amp 7 \amp 19\\8 \amp 18 \amp 4 \amp 18\\ 21 \amp 1 \amp 17 \amp 9\end{bmatrix}
                    </md>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Is <m>M + R</m> also a magic square?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What about <m>M - R</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can you explain why or why not?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculating <m>M + R</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> M + R \amp = \begin{bmatrix}16 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp 13\\ 5 \amp 10 \amp 11 \amp 8 \\ 9 \amp 6 \amp 7 \amp 12 \\ 4 \amp 15 \amp 14 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 16 \amp 10 \amp 20 \amp 2 \\3 \amp 19 \amp 7 \amp 19\\8 \amp 18 \amp 4 \amp 18\\ 21 \amp 1 \amp 17 \amp 9\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}32 \amp 13 \amp 22 \amp 15 \\ 8 \amp 29 \amp 18 \amp 27 \\17 \amp 24 \amp 11 \amp 30 \\ 25 \amp 16 \amp 31 \amp 10\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Checking all the rows and columns and diagonals, they each add up to 82, and thus <m>M + R</m> is a magic square.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculating <m>M - R</m>:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> M - R \amp = \begin{bmatrix}16 \amp 3 \amp 2 \amp 13\\ 5 \amp 10 \amp 11 \amp 8 \\ 9 \amp 6 \amp 7 \amp 12 \\ 4 \amp 15 \amp 14 \amp 1\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 16 \amp 10 \amp 20 \amp 2 \\3 \amp 19 \amp 7 \amp 19\\8 \amp 18 \amp 4 \amp 18\\ 21 \amp 1 \amp 17 \amp 9\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \amp -7 \amp -18 \amp 11 \\ 2 \amp -9 \amp 4 \amp -11 \\1 \amp -12 \amp 3 \amp -6 \\ -17 \amp 14 \amp -3 \amp -8\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                                </md>
                                Checking all the rows and columns and diagonals, they each add up to <m>-14</m>, and thus <m>M - R</m> is a magic square.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Consider the first row in <m>M + R</m>. The sum of the entries is the sum of the entries in the first row of <m>M</m> (34) and the sum of the entries in the first row of <m>R</m> (48), which will give <m>34+48 = 82</m>. This will be true for every other row (and column and diagonal), since <m>M</m> and <m>R</m> are magic.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The same logic applies to <m>M - R</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

